        "## Anomaly Detection Threshold and Evaluation\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "Here, we determined a threshold for detecting anomalous transactions. For example, if the transaction exceeds the determined threshold, then the transaction would be flagged as a potential fraud by our model.\n",
        "\n",
        "Used a *confusion matrix* to represent model's performance:\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "*   True Positive (Top Left): Correctly identified normal transaction\n",
        "*   False Positive (Bottom Left): Incorrectly identified normal transaction\n",
        "*   False Negative (Top Right): Incorrectly identified fraudulant transaction\n",
        "*   True Negative (Bottom Right): Correctly identified fraudulant transaction\n",
        "\n",
        "========\n",
        "\n",
        "| TP  |  FN |\n",
        "\n",
        "========\n",
        "\n",
        "| FP  |  TN |\n",
        "\n",
        "========\n",
        "\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"
        },
        "id": "fbcf7425",
        "outputId": "246a3c0b-a168-44fe-a864-54c08780a35c"
      },
      "source": [
        "from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix, precision_recall_fscore_support\n",
        "\n",
        "# Determine a suitable threshold for anomaly detection\n",
        "# A more robust approach is to use a percentile of the reconstruction errors from the validation set\n",
        "threshold = np.percentile(mse_val, 95) # Using the 95th percentile\n",
        "\n",
        "print(f\"Anomaly detection threshold: {threshold:.4f}\")\n",
        "\n",
        "# Classify transactions based on the threshold\n",
        "# Reconstruct errors for all transactions (X_train, X_val, fraud_transactions)\n",
        "# For simplicity, let's concatenate mse_train and mse_val to represent 'normal' errors\n",
        "all_normal_mse = np.concatenate([mse_train, mse_val])\n",
        "# Note: all_X is not used in the metrics calculation but was concatenated previously\n",
        "# all_X = pd.concat([X_train, X_val, fraud_transactions])\n",
        "\n",
        "# Create true labels for the combined dataset\n",
        "# Assuming all_normal_mse corresponds to y=0 and mse_fraud corresponds to y=1\n",
        "true_labels = np.concatenate([np.zeros(len(all_normal_mse)), np.ones(len(mse_fraud))])\n",
        "predicted_errors = np.concatenate([all_normal_mse, mse_fraud])\n",
        "\n",
        "# Predict anomalies\n",
        "predictions = (predicted_errors > threshold).astype(int)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Evaluate the model\n",
        "conf_matrix = confusion_matrix(true_labels, predictions)\n",
        "precision, recall, f1_score, _ = precision_recall_fscore_support(true_labels, predictions, average='binary', zero_division=0)\n",
        "\n",
        "print(\"\\nConfusion Matrix:\")\n",
        "print(conf_matrix)\n",
        "print(f\"\\nPrecision: {precision:.4f}\")\n",
        "print(f\"Recall: {recall:.4f}\")\n",
        "print(f\"F1-Score: {f1_score:.4f}\")\n"
      ],
